		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Choosing the Right: Legolas<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.46)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223'>Joseph "Telcontar" Albers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 11, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">   To start off, I would like to again thank everyone who responded to my last article (it would seem that I was not completely right about Slinker, sorry). Oh well, on to Legolas:<br />
<br />
1. Legolas, Greenleaf (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Frodo<br />
   Archer. Archery: Exert Legolas to wound<br />
   a minion; Legolas does not add to the <br />
   fellowship archery total.<br />
<br />
 Perhaps the best of the bunch, Greenleaf is without a doubt one of the games top companions. He can deal out an archery wound by himself or exert to kill off specific minions. Give him a Tale of Gil-galad and he can shoot an extra time. He fits into many different decktypes and can be easily started with Gimli, Arwen, Glorfindel, and many other powerful characters.<br />
<br />
2. Legolas, Prince of Mirkwood (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Gandalf<br />
   Archer. While skirmishing a Nazgul, Legolas<br />
   is strength +3.<br />
<br />
 A weaker version, PoM does have his uses. He is basically a DoE w/the Gandalf signet (and he swaps being an archer for being a ranger). Why then is he not played? Simply because Greenleaf and other Legolases are just better. PoM is a strong companion, especially in a Nazgul meta, but a weak Legolas. Could be used in a Trust deck, but Elven Comrade is more useful.<br />
<br />
3. Legolas, Son of Thranduil (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Aragorn<br />
   Archer. While Legolas is at a river or forest,<br />
   add 1 to the fellowship archery total.<br />
<br />
 Although extremely popular during the days of the fellowship block, SoT has become all but forgotten. With only two forest sites in TT and two rivers in RotK, there is almost no point in playing him when there are better Leggys out there. The Legolas of choice in a fellowship block archery deck, SoT has basically no other uses.<br />
<br />
4. Legolas, Dauntless Hunter (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Aragorn<br />
   Archer. The twilight cost of each Shadow<br />
   event and Shadow condition is +1 for each<br />
   unbound Hobbit you can spot.<br />
<br />
 The ultimate choke companion, Dauntless Hunter has become one of the most powerful and popular decks out there. His ability to start with Merry and Pippin already out has made it possible to choke condition heavy decks from the get go. Dauntless Hunter&#39;s only real weaknesses are possession heavy Shadows (namely Corsairs and Shelob). However, Rohirrim Road is also available to help with possessions. If this is not enough, DH is also an archer and if your opponent is choked, his few minions will be very vulnerable to archery. Dauntless Hunter ranks with Greenleaf as the top Leggys.<br />
<br />
5. Legolas, Elven Comrade (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Gandalf<br />
   Archer. Skirmish: Exert Legolas to make a<br />
   minion skirmishing an unbound companion <br />
   strength -1 (or -2 if that companion is <br />
   Gimli).<br />
<br />
 The Trust Legolas. Elven Comrade is capable of weakening any minion that is giving unbound companions trouble. He can start with Gimli, Unbidden Guest for possibly the best 1-2 punch in the game. With Final Count and My Axe Is Notched out, EC and UG are a force to be reckoned with. Elven Comrade is one of the fighting Legolases and one of the most useful.<br />
<br />
6. Legolas, Archer of Mirkwood (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Theoden<br />
   Archer. Each time Legolas wins a skirmish, you<br />
   may heal a Dwarf companion or another Elf <br />
   companion.<br />
<br />
 A somewhat underplayed Leggy, AoM can be very effective with Unbidden Guest. Simply exert Gimli to get the +2 you need to win a skirmish and then heal Gimli, rinse and repeat. He is probably the Legolas of choice in a fighting Naith deck in conjunction with UG, but is not much use elsewhere. Overall, Archer of Mirkwood can be successful in a specialized deck, but there are better Leggys out there.<br />
<br />
7. Legolas, Fearless Marksman (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Aragorn<br />
   Archer. Archery: If you have initiative, discard<br />
   4 cards from hand to wound a minion.<br />
<br />
 Although overpowered at first glance, Fearless Marksman is not that good. Sure, he&#39;s an archer and can wound an extra minion for the price of 4 cards, but let&#39;s face it, you will almost never use this more than once per turn and it will lose you initiative almost every time. Decent, but I&#39;ll take Greenleaf any day.<br />
<br />
8. Legolas, Nimble Warrior (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Theoden<br />
   Archer. Archery: If you cannot spot a threat,<br />
   add a threat to make the fellowship archery<br />
   total +1.<br />
<br />
 Not bad. If you are running a threat control fellowship, Nimble Warrior can consistently give out 2 archery per turn. He can be used in a Shake Off the Shadow/Reckless We Rode deck for maximum potential. Other than that, he is not much use, although he could possibly fit into a Greatest Stronghold/pre-skirmish wounding deck. Nimble Warrior is, on the whole, one of the more specialized Legolases.<br />
<br />
9. Legolas, Elven Stalwart (2)<br />
   Companion Elf<br />
   Str. 6 Vit. 3 Sig. Aragorn<br />
   Archer. While you can spot 3 wounded minions,<br />
   each minion skirmishing Legolas is strength<br />
   -3.<br />
<br />
 Interesting. An extremely conditionally powerful Legolas. If you can manage to wound 3 different minions, Elven Stalwart will take on anything that is thrown against him. Wounding 3 different minions is difficult, especially if your opponent is smart and has minions with large vitality. Although he could encourage wounding fewer minions more, activating Elven Stalwart&#39;s text is tricky at best. Against Shadow sides like Dunland and Moria, he is all but useless, except for a single archery wound. Once again, there are better Leggys out there.<br />
<br />
 Whew! That&#39;s a lot of Leggys! Hope I haven&#39;t lost you. Of course, my Legolas rankings:<br />
<br />
1. Legolas, Dauntless Hunter<br />
2. Legolas, Greenleaf<br />
3. Legolas, Elven Comrade<br />
4. Legolas, Nimble Warrior<br />
5. Legolas, Archer of Mirkwood<br />
6. Legolas, Prince of Mirkwood<br />
7. Legolas, Fearless Marksman<br />
8. Legolas, Elven Stalwart<br />
9. Legolas, Son of Thranduil<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading and thanks in advance for all reviews!<br />
<br />
Telcontar.<br />
<br />
&quot;In the high tongue it will not sound so ill&quot;<br />
<br />
Up next: I&#39;m not sure yet. Suggestions for a companion/ally in your reviews are welcome.<br />
